ARTICLES

Replication of the Spread of True and False News Online

September 1, 2018

According to the data and code shared by the researchers, I replicate the results of the study.

Access to the paper:http://science.sciencemag.org/content/359/6380/1146

Author

Soroush Vosoughi, Deb Roy, Sinan Aral

Central Findings

They found that false news was more novel than true news, which suggests that people were more likely to share novel information. Whereas false stories inspired fear, disgust, and surprise in replies, true stories inspired anticipation, sadness, joy, and trust. Contrary to conventional wisdom, robots accelerated the spread of true and false news at the same rate, implying that false news spreads more than the truth because humans, not robots, are more likely to spread it.

Data

The data comprise 126,000 stories tweeted by 3 million people more than 4.5 million times.
